The morphology of the assembled La-BDC/rGO/GQDs@mingled hydrogel beads nanocomposite was characterized from the SEM along with HR-TEM studies. In the represented (Fig. 1e
                        ), the SEM shows aggregation of the particles to refer to hydrogel synthesis that linked all the molecules. Such image confirms the occurrence of micro pores to assist in the adsorption interactions. Moreover, the HR-TEM image illustrates that at low magnification, the particles are uniformly distributed, while at large magnification, the aggregation of the particles was demonstrated providing particles size 25.3 nm as clarified in Fig. 1f
                        . Finally, the EDX spectrum (Fig. 1g
                        ) was employed to detect the composition proportions in the assembled nanocomposite including carbon mass proportion (19.32 %), oxygen (52.11 %), La (5.20 %), Ca (19.92 %) and Na (3.44 %) to confirm that the nanocomposite was successfully and correctly synthesized [3].

The linear besides nonlinear kinetic patterns were examined to explore the uranium (VI) capturing interaction type of with La-BDC/rGO/GQDs@mingled hydrogel nanocomposite to identify the most convenient model. The resulting kinetic results (theoretical besides practical) are correlated to the specific R2 magnitudes. Usually, the elevated R2 confirms the most kinetic model to matching the adsorptive capture interaction of uranyl with La-BDC/rGO/GQDs@mingled hydrogel nanocomposite. The pseudo-first order [56] was examined and the graphs at Fig. 3a
                            formed a line with slope k1 magnitude to determine the R2 values as 0.9146 & 0.9549 (Table 1
                           ) at 100 & 50 mg /L uranyl concentration, correspondingly. Thus, pseudo-first order could be identified as a non-fitting pattern to describe the capture interaction. Also, the characterized and calculated capture efficiency at equilibrium (qecal) and experimental (qeexp) values were not coincide (Table 2
                           ). The pseudo-second order pattern was examined [57] and clarified at Fig. 3b
                            as t/qt was sketched versus time to give 1/qe slope in addition to /k2qe
                           2 intercept. The identified R2 = 0.9609 & 0.9566 by 100 & 50 mg/ L uranyl concentrations, correspondingly. This pattern was utilized to symbolize the uranyl capture onto La-BDC/rGO/GQDs@mingled hydrogel nanocomposite as (qecal) is fitting with the magnitudes of (qeexp) as compiled (Table 2).

The Ce (mg. L−1) parameter indicating the U(VI) concentration at settlement, qe (mg/g) is the captured uranyl by La-BDC/rGO/GQDs@mingled hydrogel nanocomposite. The linear correlation provides lnKD & 1/T as the slope & intercept for computation ΔH° and ΔS°, correspondingly, (Fig. 6b
                           ). As listed in Table 6
                           , the ΔG° value was obtained with a negative sign to indicate a spontaneous adsorptive capture process of U(VI). Moreover, the positive ΔS° value elucidates the enhancing in disorderliness by the adsorptive capture of U(VI) onto La-BDC/rGO/GQDs@mingled hydrogel nanocomposite, whist the positive magnitude of (ΔH°) affirms and provides more evidence for the endothermic capture type of interaction [65].
